





ST-T1024 Sovereign Core: 
RISC-V Implementation


1. Executive Summary: The Sovereign RISC-V Core
The ST-T1024 architecture is a sovereign, deterministic intelligence standard. By moving
from software emulation to RISC-V silicon, we bypass the stochastic limitations of
cloud-based, GPU-dependent AI. This implementation utilizes custom instructions to enable
1.58-bit ternary inference, enforcing a strict WCET (Worst-Case Execution Time) of
<800\text{ns} per query.



2. Core Principles
● Custom ISA (CISA): Ternary-logic primitives added via RISC-V custom-0 opcodes.
● Deterministic Flow: Execution governed by a hardware-level Finite State Machine
(FSM).
● Zero-OS Overhead: Direct-to-metal execution on Tightly Coupled Memory (TCM).
● Immutable Knowledge: 75% of model weights are burned into ROM for auditability.



3. Implementation Procedure: From Standard to Silicon
This guide outlines the "Beginner-to-Sovereign" path. If you can write basic C and
understand a simple state machine, you can implement this.

Phase A: Defining the Ternary Logic (RTL)
1. Select Base Core: Use an open-source RISC-V core such as NEORV32 or Pulpino.
2. Create the TTERN Module:
○ Write a Verilog module that accepts two input registers (ternary values -1, 0,
1).
○ Implement the ternary-accumulate function: Sum += (Input1 * Input2).
○ Synthesize this module as a "Custom Functional Unit" within the core's
Execute stage.

Phase B: Extending the Toolchain
1. Add Opcodes: Update your riscv-opcodes file to reserve space for TTERN.ADD and
TTERN.XNOR.
2. Update Binutils/GCC: Modify the RISC-V GNU toolchain configuration to recognize
these new instructions. (Detailed guide: Adding Custom Instructions to RISC-V ISA).

Phase C: Mapping the FSM
1. State Encoding: Assign a 4-bit register for the FSM state.
2. Pipeline Integration: Ensure your state machine gates the TTERN execution.
○ IDLE -> ROUTING -> INFER -> OUTPUT -> POWER_DOWN.
3. Deterministic Enforcement: Set the logic to "Halt" or "Power Gate" once the FSM
reaches the POWER_DOWN state, preventing further cycles from wasting power or
introducing drift.

Phase D: Simulation & Verification
1. Emulate: Use Renode or Spike to load your binary.
2. Verify: Run the Phi-3 weight-tiles against the emulator output. If the hardware output
matches your Python reference implementation bit-for-bit, your implementation is
ST-T1024 Compliant.



